  "prompt": "If [math]1\\circ4=5[/math] and [math]2\\circ5=12[/math] and [math]3\\circ6=21[/math] then what is [math]8\\circ11[/math]? Fun\u2026",
  "response": "This looks like a puzzle where the operator \\(\\circ\\) represents a pattern or rule that isn't immediately obvious. Let's try to find a consistent rule based on the given examples:\n\n1. \\(1 \\circ 4 = 5\\)\n2. \\(2 \\circ 5 = 12\\)\n3. \\(3 \\circ 6 = 21\\)\n\nTo find the rule, let's examine the pairs and their results:\n\nFor \\(1 \\circ 4 = 5\\):\n- Notice that \\(1 \\times 4 = 4\\)\n- Adding the first number \\(1\\) gives \\(4 + 1 = 5\\)\n\nFor \\(2 \\circ 5 = 12\\):\n- Notice that \\(2 \\times 5 = 10\\)\n- Adding the first number \\(2\\) gives \\(10 + 2 = 12\\)\n\nFor \\(3 \\circ 6 = 21\\):\n- Notice that \\(3 \\times 6 = 18\\)\n- Adding the first number \\(3\\) gives \\(18 + 3 = 21\\)\n\nSo the pattern seems to be that \\(a \\circ b = (a \\times b) + a\\).\n\nUsing this pattern for \\(8 \\circ 11\\):\n\n\\[ 8 \\circ 11 = (8 \\times 11) + 8 = 88 + 8 = 96 \\]\n\nThus, \\(8 \\circ 11 = 96\\).",
